      Bribes
   =20
 =20
If you work in sales in an out-of-the-way geography in a large multinationa=
l public corporation, two things that you will be told a lot are:=09Win lot=
s of business!=09Don=E2=80=99t pay bribes!In general, your company really m=
eans both of these things. Winning business is obviously very good; it is h=
ow your company makes money. Not paying bribes is also=C2=A0quite important=
; if you pay bribes your company might get in lots of trouble and have to p=
ay much more in fines than you ever brought in in revenue, plus you might g=
o to prison. Your bosses will tell you both of these things and mean them, =
and you will go out with noble intentions to win lots of business and not p=
ay bribes.There is, however, an asymmetry here. If you come back to your bo=
sses and say =E2=80=9CI won lots of business,=E2=80=9D they will give you a=
 big bonus and a promotion; if you come back and say =E2=80=9CI have won no=
 business,=E2=80=9D they will fire you. If you come back to your bosses and=
 say =E2=80=9CI paid no bribes at all,=E2=80=9D you will not get a big bonu=
s or a promotion. =E2=80=9CSure, right, we don=E2=80=99t pay bribes,=E2=80=
=9D your bosses will say; =E2=80=9Cwhy are you even mentioning this?=E2=80=
=9D You will not be celebrated for avoiding bribery in the way you will be =
for winning business, and you will get the impression that your bosses care=
 more about winning business than about avoiding bribes.Meanwhile if you co=
me to your bosses and say =E2=80=9CI paid lots of bribes=E2=80=9D they will=
=C2=A0absolutely also fire you and send you to prison, but there are ways n=
ot to=C2=A0tell them. =E2=80=9CI have hired a local consultant to advise on=
 how to navigate this country=E2=80=99s public contracting process; I will =
need to expense their $1 million consulting fee and also a burlap sack to p=
ut it in.=E2=80=9D Your large multinational public corporation will absolut=
ely have processes in place to prevent this! But they are somewhat porous, =
in a way that their process for firing people who don=E2=80=99t win=C2=A0an=
y business are not.If you go out and win lots of business without paying br=
ibes hey that=E2=80=99s great. But at some point =E2=80=94=C2=A0particularl=
y if you are not a local, you don=E2=80=99t have deep ties to the networks =
of money and power in the local economy, you don=E2=80=99t know your way ar=
ound the local customs, your big company=E2=80=99s name doesn=E2=80=99t car=
ry the clout here that it does in its home geographies, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0you might find yourself forced to choose between (1) paying bribes and w=
inning business or (2) not paying bribes and not winning business. The corr=
ect answer is (2)! Don=E2=80=99t pay the bribes! This is not legal advice p=
er se, but I=E2=80=99m sure it=E2=80=99s what your lawyer would tell you. Y=
ou might feel pressure to go with (1) though. You are a social creature see=
king the approval of your peers and bosses, and you think you can see what =
they=C2=A0really=C2=A0approve of.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CI will just pay some bribes=
, get a big promotion, and leave this out-of-the-way geography as a hero,=
=E2=80=9D you tell yourself.I feel like former Goldman Sachs Group Inc. ban=
ker Tim Leissner is near the top of the all-time global league table for pa=
ying bribes?=C2=A0Leissner led Goldman=E2=80=99s efforts to raise about $6 =
billion of bonds for Malaysia=E2=80=99s 1MDB fund, most of which was allege=
dly  handed over directly to Malaysian politicians and fund insiders. Goldm=
an, meanwhile, made about $600 million in fees on the deal. Paying $6 billi=
on of bribes for a $600 million fee may not seem like good business, but re=
member the $6 billion came from someone else (initially bondholders, though=
 in theory eventually=C2=A0the Malaysian people) and the $600 million went =
to Goldman. (It was not good business:=C2=A0Goldman ended up  paying billio=
ns of fines and restitution.) Also Leissner apparently collected at least $=
50 million=C2=A0for himself=C2=A0from the deals.[1] He was charged criminal=
ly in the U.S., pleaded guilty and is now testifying against his former col=
league=C2=A0for allegedly doing the same thing. Yesterday Leissner explaine=
d why he did it:Timothy Leissner told a federal jury in New York that he an=
d former colleague Roger Ng received praise from Goldman executives by secu=
ring three deals in 2012 and 2013 to raise $6.5 billion in bond offerings f=
or 1Malaysia Development Bhd., a state-controlled economic development comp=
any known as 1MDB. Goldman earned more than $600 million in fees and revenu=
e, at the time an unprecedented amount for the bank=E2=80=99s southeast Asi=
a division, Mr. Leissner said.But Mr. Leissner said he and Mr. Ng hid from =
Goldman executives the role of a controversial Malaysian financier [Jho Low=
] in the deal and a scheme to pay bribes to government officials in Malaysi=
a and the United Arab Emirates.=E2=80=9CI knew it was illegal,=E2=80=9D he =
said. =E2=80=9CI wanted this to be done for Goldman Sachs. I wanted to be a=
 hero at Goldman Sachs.=E2=80=9D ...Before the first bond offering, Messrs.=
 Low, Leissner and Ng met in London, where Mr. Low sketched out on a piece =
of paper the officials in Malaysia and Abu Dhabi who needed to be bribed, M=
r. Leissner testified.The list included former Malaysian Prime Minister Naj=
ib Razak, according to Mr. Leissner. Mr. Razak was later accused of embezzl=
ing more than $680 million from the 1MDB fund. He was sentenced in 2020 to =
12 years imprisonment after a court in his country found him guilty of abus=
e of power.Mr. Leissner said he wasn=E2=80=99t surprised by the need for br=
ibes, saying he believed they were somewhat common in Asia. He was also awa=
re the bribes were illegal, he said, but the deals brought him praise.=E2=
=80=9CThey were highlighted at the highest level at Goldman Sachs,=E2=80=9D=
 he said.And:Leissner described a high-pressure environment at Goldman wher=
e bankers who missed out on business would be required to formally explain =
to management why. It was =E2=80=9Cingrained in us it was unacceptable to l=
ose business=E2=80=9D, he said.If you bring in $600 million of revenue in a=
 challenging place where it=E2=80=99s historically been hard to win busines=
s, you will get calls from senior management telling you what a good job yo=
u did. If you don=E2=80=99t, you will also get calls from your bosses, but =
they will be much less pleasant. And no one will call you up to be like =E2=
=80=9Cgood job not paying bribes.=E2=80=9D One choice gets you praise, the =
other does not. He chose praise, the wrong choice and yet understandable. T=
o be fair he also chose to pay himself $50 million of the bribes.Elsewhere =
if your job is to, like, install a wireless network in ISIS-controlled area=
s of Iraq =E2=80=A6 I don=E2=80=99t know,  possibly you should just get a d=
ifferent job?=C2=A0Ericsson may have made payments to the ISIS terror organ=
ization to gain access to certain transport routes in Iraq, in a shock admi=
ssion following years of regulatory investigations.Shares in the Stockholm-=
based company were down almost 14.5% around lunchtime on Wednesday, its big=
gest drop in a day since July 2017. ...In an interview with newspaper Dagen=
s Industri, chief executive officer Borje Ekholm said that Ericsson had ide=
ntified =E2=80=9Cunusual expenses dating back to 2018=E2=80=9D but the comp=
any hasn=E2=80=99t yet determined who the final recipient of the money was.=
 =E2=80=9CWhat we are seeing is that transport routes have been purchased t=
hrough areas that have been controlled by terrorist organizations, includin=
g ISIS,=E2=80=9D Ekholm added. =E2=80=A6Ekholm told the newspaper that Eric=
sson has spent =E2=80=9Cconsiderable resources trying to understand this as=
 best we can. Financing terrorism is completely unacceptable and something =
we do not allow at all.=E2=80=9DYou never really want to find yourself sayi=
ng =E2=80=9Cfinancing terrorism is completely unacceptable and something we=
 do not allow at all.=E2=80=9D That means some of your employees got a diff=
erent message!
