      Shorting, spoofing, scalping
   =20
 =20
Let=E2=80=99s say you think that there=E2=80=99s a 70% probability that a=
=C2=A0publicly traded company is a fraud and worth zero. A reasonable thing=
 to do might be to short the stock, betting that it will go down. Another r=
easonable thing to do, after you short the stock might be to publish a repo=
rt saying =E2=80=9Cthis company is a fraud and worth zero=E2=80=9D and layi=
ng out your evidence. If you do that, the market might react. The stock mig=
ht go down.If you shorted the stock at $50, thinking there was a 70% chance=
 it would be worth zero, then you probably had an expectation of making abo=
ut $35 of profit ($50 minus $0, times 70%). But it will take you a while to=
 realize that profit: Regulators will have to investigate, they are sometim=
es slow, and meanwhile the company will yell at you and retail investors wi=
ll try to squeeze shorts. A lot can go wrong while you wait to be proven ri=
ght. That $35 of expected profit is=C2=A0years away and you have a pretty h=
igh discount rate. If someone came to you and said =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ll pa=
y you $20 now to get out of this position,=E2=80=9D you=E2=80=99d probably =
take it. You=E2=80=99re leaving some money on the table, but you=E2=80=99re=
 avoiding a lot of risk and headache. Short selling is a difficult business=
 and if you can get some easy wins you might want to take them.If the stock=
 goes down to $30 on the day you release your report, then someone (the mar=
ket)=C2=A0is=C2=A0offering you $20 to take your bet off the table. You shou=
ld take it! You short at $50, put out a report, buy back at $30, collect yo=
ur $20 reward for pointing out problems with the company, and move on to ot=
her things. Eventually when the stock goes to zero you can put out a little=
 note saying =E2=80=9Csee I was right, no need to thank me.=E2=80=9D Or if =
the stock goes back to $60 and it turns out not to be a fraud, you quietly =
say =E2=80=9Cphew, got that one wrong, glad I got out when I did, sorry eve=
ryone.=E2=80=9DIdeally this would only work if your reports were good. If y=
ou put out a report saying =E2=80=9Cthis company is a total fraud=E2=80=9D =
and you were wrong, an efficient market would quickly assess your report an=
d decide it was bogus, and the stock would not drop. You=E2=80=99d have no =
immediate profit, and no long-term profit either, and you=E2=80=99d eventua=
lly go out of business because you are bad at short selling and that is not=
 a forgiving business.But of course=C2=A0markets are not entirely efficient=
 and it is certainly not impossible for an incorrect short report to drive =
the stock price down, at least in the short term. And if you write that sho=
rt report and cover your shorts when it comes out, that is kind of a bad lo=
ok.=C2=A0Anyway here is=C2=A0kind of a weird Wall Street Journal story:Fede=
ral prosecutors are investigating whether short-sellers conspired to drive =
down stock prices by sharing damaging research reports ahead of time and en=
gaging in illegal trading tactics, people familiar with the matter said.The=
 U.S. Justice Department has seized hardware, trading records and private c=
ommunications in an effort to prove a wide-ranging conspiracy among investo=
rs who bet against corporate shares, the people said. One tactic under inve=
stigation is =E2=80=9Cspoofing,=E2=80=9D an illegal ploy that involves floo=
ding the market with fake orders in an effort to push a stock price up or d=
own, they said. Another is =E2=80=9Cscalping,=E2=80=9D where activist short=
-sellers cash out their positions without disclosing it.Yeah, like I said, =
I can see how scalping, or scalping-adjacent behavior, would rub people the=
 wrong way. At DealBook the other day, Michelle Celarier had a good=C2=A0de=
fense of activist short selling that was sympathetic to the idea that they =
sometimes need to cover their shorts soon after publishing negative researc=
h:Short sellers have long been told by their lawyers that as long as their =
reports contain no material inaccuracies and are not based on inside inform=
ation, they have done nothing illegal. In the disclosure accompanying their=
 reports, activist short sellers typically say they are short the stock but=
 may cover at any time. And they add that they are not offering investment =
advice.John Courtade, a former senior S.E.C. enforcement litigator who now =
represents short sellers, has designed some of these disclosures. =E2=80=9C=
Scalping has to involve deception of some sort,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9C=
Just the fact that you=E2=80=99re going to close your position has never be=
en held to be deception. If you look at the cases, they involve situations =
like not disclosing that you have a position at all.=E2=80=9DBut, sure, peo=
ple get annoyed.Spoofing, though? From the Journal:Spoofing is essentially =
high-speed bluffing, in which one trader dupes others into transacting at a=
rtificially high or low prices. A spoofer, for example, might offer to sell=
 a big block of shares at $10 when the last sale was at $10.03. After other=
 sellers rush to match the lower price, the spoofer quickly pivots, canceli=
ng his sell order and instead buying at the $10 price he generated with the=
 fake bid. Repeated enough times, spoofing can produce big profits. ...Colu=
mbia Law School professor Joshua Mitts, who published a 2020 academic paper=
 entitled =E2=80=9CShort and Distort=E2=80=9D that was critical of short-se=
lling tactics, has been advising the Justice Department in its investigatio=
n, people familiar with the matter said. Mr. Mitts has in the past also ser=
ved as an expert for companies and executives, including Farmland Partners =
Inc. and Banc of California=E2=80=99s former CEO, that have sued short-sell=
ers, alleging they promoted false or misleading research.Analyses performed=
 by Mr. Mitts on those companies=E2=80=94prepared in private litigation, no=
t for the Justice Department investigation=E2=80=94show that in the moments=
 around the release of a short-seller report, heavy volumes of sell orders =
are sent to exchanges and then canceled within fractions of a second, accor=
ding to documents reviewed by The Wall Street Journal. That behavior, Mr. M=
itts argues in the documents, is a telltale sign of spoofing.What? Why? Wha=
t? Two things about spoofing are:=09It is a way to trade on=C2=A0the other =
side. If you put in a lot of fake sell orders, it=E2=80=99s because you wan=
t to buy. Maybe the accusation here is that short sellers get short, put ou=
t negative reports, spoof the price down with big fake sell orders and then=
 buy back at the lower price?=C2=A0=09It is=C2=A0small-scale, in both price=
 and time. Spoofing is a way to buy stock at $10.00 instead of $10.03; it=
=E2=80=99s a way to save a couple of pennies, at most, on a trade. If you a=
re making your living as a criminal spoofer you are doing it=C2=A0a lot, ba=
ck and forth all day every day. If you are an activist short seller the way=
 you make the stock go down is by=C2=A0publishing your report, and if that =
works the stock goes down=C2=A0a lot,=C2=A0once. Adding spoofing to that do=
esn't really make sense.
