<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note:</strong> <em>Money S=
tuff will be off tomorrow and Monday, back on Tuesday.</em></p><table class=
=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0"=
>
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Bribes</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you work in sales in an out-of-the-=
way geography in a large multinational public corporation, two things that =
you will be told a lot are:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; paddi=
ng-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Win lo=
ts of business!</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Don=E2=80=99t pay =
bribes!</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>In general</em>, your com=
pany really means both of these things. Winning business is obviously very =
good; it is how your company makes money. Not paying bribes is also=C2=A0qu=
ite important; if you pay bribes your company might get in lots of trouble =
and have to pay much more in fines than you ever brought in in revenue, plu=
s you might go to prison. Your bosses will tell you both of these things an=
d mean them, and you will go out with noble intentions to win lots of busin=
ess and not pay bribes.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is, however, =
an asymmetry here. If you come back to your bosses and say =E2=80=9CI won l=
ots of business,=E2=80=9D they will give you a big bonus and a promotion; i=
f you come back and say =E2=80=9CI have won no business,=E2=80=9D they will=
 fire you. If you come back to your bosses and say =E2=80=9CI paid no bribe=
s at all,=E2=80=9D you will not get a big bonus or a promotion. =E2=80=9CSu=
re, right, we don=E2=80=99t pay bribes,=E2=80=9D your bosses will say; =E2=
=80=9Cwhy are you even mentioning this?=E2=80=9D You will not be celebrated=
 for avoiding bribery in the way you will be for winning business, and you =
will get the impression that your bosses care more about winning business t=
han about avoiding bribes.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile if you=
 come to your bosses and say =E2=80=9CI paid lots of bribes=E2=80=9D they w=
ill=C2=A0<em>absolutely also fire you and send you to prison</em>, but ther=
e are ways not to=C2=A0tell them. =E2=80=9CI have hired a local consultant =
to advise on how to navigate this country=E2=80=99s public contracting proc=
ess; I will need to expense their $1 million consulting fee and also a burl=
ap sack to put it in.=E2=80=9D Your large multinational public corporation =
will absolutely have processes in place to prevent this! But they are somew=
hat porous, in a way that their process for firing people who don=E2=80=99t=
 win=C2=A0any business are not.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you go o=
ut and win lots of business without paying bribes hey that=E2=80=99s great.=
 But at some point =E2=80=94=C2=A0particularly if you are not a local, you =
don=E2=80=99t have deep ties to the networks of money and power in the loca=
l economy, you don=E2=80=99t know your way around the local customs, your b=
ig company=E2=80=99s name doesn=E2=80=99t carry the clout here that it does=
 in its home geographies, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0you might find yourself force=
d to choose between (1) paying bribes and winning business or (2) not payin=
g bribes and not winning business. The correct answer is (2)! Don=E2=80=99t=
 pay the bribes! This is not legal advice per se, but I=E2=80=99m sure it=
=E2=80=99s what your lawyer would tell you. You might feel pressure to go w=
ith (1) though. You are a social creature seeking the approval of your peer=
s and bosses, and you think you can see what they=C2=A0<em>really=C2=A0</em=
>approve of.=C2=A0=E2=80=9CI will just pay some bribes, get a big promotion=
, and leave this out-of-the-way geography as a hero,=E2=80=9D you tell your=
self.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I feel like former Goldman Sachs Grou=
p Inc. banker Tim Leissner is near the top of the all-time global league ta=
ble for paying bribes?=C2=A0Leissner led Goldman=E2=80=99s efforts to raise=
 about $6 billion of bonds for Malaysia=E2=80=99s 1MDB fund, most of which =
was allegedly <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2674=
5806.281599/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTg=
tMTEtMDIvZG9uLXQtc3RlYWwtdGhlLWJyaWJlLW1vbmV5P2NtcGlkPUJCRDAyMTcyMl9NT05FWV=
NUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyM=
DIxNyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe0064e5c" it=
emprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #=
ccc;"> handed over directly to Malaysian politicians and fund insiders</a>.=
 Goldman, meanwhile, made about $600 million in fees on the deal. Paying $6=
 billion of bribes for a $600 million fee may not seem like good business, =
but remember the $6 billion came from someone else (initially bondholders, =
though in theory eventually=C2=A0the Malaysian people) and the $600 million=
 went to Goldman. (It was not good business:=C2=A0Goldman ended up <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26745806.281599/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjAtMDctMjQvZ29sZG1hbi1k=
b2VzLWEtbWFsYXlzaWEtZGVhbD9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMjE3MjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXV=
tPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjAyMTcmdXRtX2NhbXBhaW=
duPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB4a202300" itemprop=3D"StoryLink"=
 itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-de=
coration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #=
000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> paying billio=
ns</a> of fines and restitution.) Also Leissner apparently collected at lea=
st $50 million=C2=A0<em>for himself</em>=C2=A0from the deals.[1] He was cha=
rged criminally in the U.S., pleaded guilty and is now testifying against h=
is former colleague=C2=A0for allegedly doing the same thing. Yesterday Leis=
sner <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26745806.2815=
99/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9mb3JtZXItZ29sZG1hbi1zYWNocy1wYXJ0=
bmVyLXRlc3RpZmllcy1hdC0xbWRiLXRyaWFsLTExNjQ1MDQ3MTY1P21vZD1pdHBfd3NqJnJ1PXl=
haG9v/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa08803a7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">explained why he did it<=
/a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Timothy Leissner told a fe=
deral jury in New York that he and former colleague Roger Ng received prais=
e from Goldman executives by securing three deals in 2012 and 2013 to raise=
 $6.5 billion in bond offerings for 1Malaysia Development Bhd., a state-con=
trolled economic development company known as 1MDB. Goldman earned more tha=
n $600 million in fees and revenue, at the time an unprecedented amount for=
 the bank=E2=80=99s southeast Asia division, Mr. Leissner said.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But Mr. Leissner said he and Mr. Ng hid from Goldman e=
xecutives the role of a controversial Malaysian financier [Jho Low] in the =
deal and a scheme to pay bribes to government officials in Malaysia and the=
 United Arab Emirates.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CI knew it w=
as illegal,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CI wanted this to be done for Goldman=
 Sachs. I wanted to be a hero at Goldman Sachs.=E2=80=9D ...</p><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">Before the first bond offering, Messrs. Low, Leissner and=
 Ng met in London, where Mr. Low sketched out on a piece of paper the offic=
ials in Malaysia and Abu Dhabi who needed to be bribed, Mr. Leissner testif=
ied.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The list included former Malaysian Pri=
me Minister Najib Razak, according to Mr. Leissner. Mr. Razak was later acc=
used of embezzling more than $680 million from the 1MDB fund. He was senten=
ced in 2020 to 12 years imprisonment after a court in his country found him=
 guilty of abuse of power.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Mr. Leissner sai=
d he wasn=E2=80=99t surprised by the need for bribes, saying he believed th=
ey were somewhat common in Asia. He was also aware the bribes were illegal,=
 he said, but the deals brought him praise.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>=E2=80=9CThey were highlighted at the highest level at Goldman Sachs,=E2=
=80=9D he said.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26745806.281599/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
ZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvOWYyN2Q3MTktMTllNS00OTQ5LTkzYWQtNWRlNzQyMjQyNDc2/607f07=
ceef4b8524a319a23cBfa9c3f04" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope"=
 target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">And</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">Leissner described a high-pressure environment at Goldman wh=
ere bankers who missed out on business would be required to formally explai=
n to management why. It was =E2=80=9Cingrained in us it was unacceptable to=
 lose business=E2=80=9D, he said.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">If you bring in $600 million of revenue in a challenging place where it=
=E2=80=99s historically been hard to win business, you will get calls from =
senior management telling you what a good job you did. If you don=E2=80=99t=
, you will also get calls from your bosses, but they will be much less plea=
sant. And no one will call you up to be like =E2=80=9Cgood job not paying b=
ribes.=E2=80=9D One choice gets you praise, the other does not. He chose pr=
aise, the wrong choice and yet understandable. To be fair he also chose to =
pay himself $50 million of the bribes.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Else=
where if your job is to, like, install a wireless network in ISIS-controlle=
d areas of Iraq =E2=80=A6 I don=E2=80=99t know, <a href=3D"https://link.mai=
l.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26745806.281599/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnL=
mNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjItMDItMTYvZXJpY3Nzb24tY2VvLWNvbmNlZGVzLWNvbXBh=
bnktbWF5LWhhdmUtcGFpZC1vZmYtaXNpcy1pbi1pcmFxP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAyMTcyMl9NT05FWVN=
UVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMD=
IxNyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB958ab9f9" ite=
mprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #c=
cc;"> possibly you should just get a different job</a>?=C2=A0</p><blockquot=
e><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ericsson may have made payments to the ISIS =
terror organization to gain access to certain transport routes in Iraq, in =
a shock admission following years of regulatory investigations.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Shares in the Stockholm-based company were down almost=
 14.5% around lunchtime on Wednesday, its biggest drop in a day since July =
2017. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In an interview with newspaper Da=
gens Industri, chief executive officer Borje Ekholm said that Ericsson had =
identified =E2=80=9Cunusual expenses dating back to 2018=E2=80=9D but the c=
ompany hasn=E2=80=99t yet determined who the final recipient of the money w=
as. =E2=80=9CWhat we are seeing is that transport routes have been purchase=
d through areas that have been controlled by terrorist organizations, inclu=
ding ISIS,=E2=80=9D Ekholm added. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>Ekholm told the newspaper that Ericsson has spent =E2=80=9Cconsiderable re=
sources trying to understand this as best we can. Financing terrorism is co=
mpletely unacceptable and something we do not allow at all.=E2=80=9D</p></b=
lockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You never really want to find yourse=
lf saying =E2=80=9Cfinancing terrorism is completely unacceptable and somet=
hing we do not allow at all.=E2=80=9D That means some of your employees got=
 a different message!</p><table class=3D"liveintent-sponsored-content" widt=
h=3D"auto" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0">
