<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Shorting, spoofing, scalping</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Let=E2=80=99s say you think that there=
=E2=80=99s a 70% probability that a=C2=A0publicly traded company is a fraud=
 and worth zero. A reasonable thing to do might be to short the stock, bett=
ing that it will go down. Another reasonable thing to do, after you short t=
he stock might be to publish a report saying =E2=80=9Cthis company is a fra=
ud and worth zero=E2=80=9D and laying out your evidence. If you do that, th=
e market might react. The stock might go down.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">If you shorted the stock at $50, thinking there was a 70% chance it wou=
ld be worth zero, then you probably had an expectation of making about $35 =
of profit ($50 minus $0, times 70%). But it will take you a while to realiz=
e that profit: Regulators will have to investigate, they are sometimes slow=
, and meanwhile the company will yell at you and retail investors will try =
to squeeze shorts. A lot can go wrong while you wait to be proven right. Th=
at $35 of expected profit is=C2=A0years away and you have a pretty high dis=
count rate. If someone came to you and said =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ll pay you $=
20 now to get out of this position,=E2=80=9D you=E2=80=99d probably take it=
. You=E2=80=99re leaving some money on the table, but you=E2=80=99re avoidi=
ng a lot of risk and headache. Short selling is a difficult business and if=
 you can get some easy wins you might want to take them.</p><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;">If the stock goes down to $30 on the day you release your rep=
ort, then someone (the market)=C2=A0<em>is=C2=A0</em>offering you $20 to ta=
ke your bet off the table. You should take it! You short at $50, put out a =
report, buy back at $30, collect your $20 reward for pointing out problems =
with the company, and move on to other things. Eventually when the stock go=
es to zero you can put out a little note saying =E2=80=9Csee I was right, n=
o need to thank me.=E2=80=9D Or if the stock goes back to $60 and it turns =
out not to be a fraud, you quietly say =E2=80=9Cphew, got that one wrong, g=
lad I got out when I did, sorry everyone.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">Ideally this would only work if your reports were good. If you put =
out a report saying =E2=80=9Cthis company is a total fraud=E2=80=9D and you=
 were wrong, an efficient market would quickly assess your report and decid=
e it was bogus, and the stock would not drop. You=E2=80=99d have no immedia=
te profit, and no long-term profit either, and you=E2=80=99d eventually go =
out of business because you are bad at short selling and that is not a forg=
iving business.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But of course=C2=A0markets =
are not entirely efficient and it is certainly not impossible for an incorr=
ect short report to drive the stock price down, at least in the short term.=
 And if you write that short report and cover your shorts when it comes out=
, that is kind of a bad look.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway =
here is=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26745=
806.281599/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9qdXN0aWNlLWRlcGFydG1lbnQt=
aXMtcHVyc3Vpbmctd2lkZS1yYW5naW5nLWludmVzdGlnYXRpb24tb2Ytc2hvcnQtc2VsbGVycy1=
zb3VyY2VzLXNheS0xMTY0NTAxOTEyMj9tb2Q9aHBfbGVhZF9wb3M2/607f07ceef4b8524a319a=
23cB46249bc3" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bla=
nk" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-botto=
m-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; bac=
kground-color: #ccc;">kind of a weird Wall Street Journal story</a>:</p><bl=
ockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Federal prosecutors are investigating=
 whether short-sellers conspired to drive down stock prices by sharing dama=
ging research reports ahead of time and engaging in illegal trading tactics=
, people familiar with the matter said.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The=
 U.S. Justice Department has seized hardware, trading records and private c=
ommunications in an effort to prove a wide-ranging conspiracy among investo=
rs who bet against corporate shares, the people said. One tactic under inve=
stigation is =E2=80=9Cspoofing,=E2=80=9D an illegal ploy that involves floo=
ding the market with fake orders in an effort to push a stock price up or d=
own, they said. Another is =E2=80=9Cscalping,=E2=80=9D where activist short=
-sellers cash out their positions without disclosing it.</p></blockquote><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yeah, like I said, I can see how scalping, or sc=
alping-adjacent behavior, would rub people the wrong way. At DealBook the o=
ther day, Michelle Celarier had a good=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/26745806.281599/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubnl0aW1lcy5jb20vM=
jAyMi8wMi8xMi9idXNpbmVzcy9kZWFsYm9vay9hcmUtYWN0aXZpc3Qtc2hvcnQtc2VsbGVycy1t=
aXN1bmRlcnN0b29kLmh0bWw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc1d1bb6f" itemprop=3D"Stor=
yLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">defense =
of activist short selling</a> that was sympathetic to the idea that they so=
metimes need to cover their shorts soon after publishing negative research:=
</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Short sellers have long been t=
old by their lawyers that as long as their reports contain no material inac=
curacies and are not based on inside information, they have done nothing il=
legal. In the disclosure accompanying their reports, activist short sellers=
 typically say they are short the stock but may cover at any time. And they=
 add that they are not offering investment advice.</p><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">John Courtade, a former senior S.E.C. enforcement litigator who now=
 represents short sellers, has designed some of these disclosures. =E2=80=
=9CScalping has to involve deception of some sort,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=
=9CJust the fact that you=E2=80=99re going to close your position has never=
 been held to be deception. If you look at the cases, they involve situatio=
ns like not disclosing that you have a position at all.=E2=80=9D</p></block=
quote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But, sure, people get annoyed.</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>Spoofing</em>, though? From the Journal:</p><blo=
ckquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Spoofing is essentially high-speed blu=
ffing, in which one trader dupes others into transacting at artificially hi=
gh or low prices. A spoofer, for example, might offer to sell a big block o=
f shares at $10 when the last sale was at $10.03. After other sellers rush =
to match the lower price, the spoofer quickly pivots, canceling his sell or=
der and instead buying at the $10 price he generated with the fake bid. Rep=
eated enough times, spoofing can produce big profits. ...</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">Columbia Law School professor Joshua Mitts, who published a =
2020 academic paper entitled =E2=80=9CShort and Distort=E2=80=9D that was c=
ritical of short-selling tactics, has been advising the Justice Department =
in its investigation, people familiar with the matter said. Mr. Mitts has i=
n the past also served as an expert for companies and executives, including=
 Farmland Partners Inc. and Banc of California=E2=80=99s former CEO, that h=
ave sued short-sellers, alleging they promoted false or misleading research=
.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Analyses performed by Mr. Mitts on those =
companies=E2=80=94prepared in private litigation, not for the Justice Depar=
tment investigation=E2=80=94show that in the moments around the release of =
a short-seller report, heavy volumes of sell orders are sent to exchanges a=
nd then canceled within fractions of a second, according to documents revie=
wed by The Wall Street Journal. That behavior, Mr. Mitts argues in the docu=
ments, is a telltale sign of spoofing.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">What? Why? What? Two things about spoofing are:</p><ol style=3D"li=
st-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It is a way to trade on=C2=A0<em>the other side</e=
m>. If you put in a lot of fake sell orders, it=E2=80=99s because you want =
to buy. Maybe the accusation here is that short sellers get short, put out =
negative reports, spoof the price down with big fake sell orders and then b=
uy back at the lower price?=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">=
It is=C2=A0<em>small-scale</em>, in both price and time. Spoofing is a way =
to buy stock at $10.00 instead of $10.03; it=E2=80=99s a way to save a coup=
le of pennies, at most, on a trade. If you are making your living as a crim=
inal spoofer you are doing it=C2=A0<em>a lot</em>, back and forth all day e=
very day. If you are an activist short seller the way you make the stock go=
 down is by=C2=A0<em>publishing your report</em>, and if that works the sto=
ck goes down=C2=A0<em>a lot</em>,=C2=A0<em>once</em>. Adding spoofing to th=
at doesn't really make sense.</li></ol><table class=3D"liveintent-flex-ad" =
